    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-06-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="21" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <head>No. 10.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Thomas O. Osborn</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-06-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 20,
                            1879</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 109.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your interesting dispatch (No. 227) of May 3
                        last has been received and read with the attention bestowed on all matters
                        having relation <pb facs="0120" n="24" xml:id="pg_24"/> to the unhappy
                        struggle which is convulsing the South American people, and which, I trust,
                        a wise statesmanship may at least restrain within its original bounds. It
                        was hoped that the boundary question between Chili and the Argentine
                        Republic, to which your dispatch more especially relates, was in a fair way
                        of settlement.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c., &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
